observations.recommendation:
a. 	The Municipal Assessor furnish the Municipal Treasurer on or before the 31st day of December of each year, an assessment roll containing a list of  all real property, whether taxable or exempt, located within the territorial jurisdiction of the Municipal Government of Libacao, Aklan and  a list of all persons whose real properties have been newly assessed or reassessed and the values of such properties;

b. 	The Municipal Treasurer prepare a duly certified list showing the name of the taxpayers and the amount due and collectible for the year and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to serve as the basis in setting up the beginning balance of RPT/SET Receivable in the books of accounts.  In such manner, the related receivable account and deferred liability will be presented fairly in the financial statements;

c. 	The Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant conduct reconciliation of records to establish a realistic balance of receivables for the RPT and SET so that necessary adjustment(s) in the books of accounts can be effected for a more realistic presentation of the balances in the financial statements;

d. 	The Municipal Treasurer religiously update the individual Real Property Tax Account Register (RPTAR) or Taxpayer’s Index Card every time a payment is received from the taxpayer which shall serve as the basis in the preparation of the List of Delinquent Real Property Taxpayers as of the end of the year, the total of which shall equal the RPT/SET Receivable at year end; and

e. 	The Municipal Accountant maintain subsidiary ledgers for RPT and SET Receivables to facilitate smooth reconciliation of balances.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Management creates an Inventory Committee purposely for the One-Time Cleansing of PPE Account Balances of Government Agencies composed of adequate number of members to be able to complete the physical inventory in three months or less. The Inventory Committee shall have at least one member from the Accounting and Property Division as required by COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
The Property and Accounting Units undertake collaborative procedures to ensure that all PPEs included in the RPCPPE are duly recorded in their respective records and that the Property Cards (PCs) maintained by the Property Unit and the PPLCs maintained by the Accounting Unit are reconciled.  The reconciliation shall be completed within 10 days from rendition of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee;
Conduct disposal of unserviceable PPEs, if there is any, by accomplishing the required Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Properties pursuant to Annex 51 of the Manual on NGAS for LGUs which will serve as the basis in dropping said items in the RPCPPE and books of accounts;
If accountability/responsibility over missing PPEs could not be pinpointed after investigation, authority for derecognition thereof from the books of accounts may be requested from the COA, in accordance with Paragraph 8 of COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
A Municipal Valuation Committee be created to determine the appraised value of donated properties and those properties found on station during the inventory taking so that these properties can be correctly recorded in the books of accounts of the municipality;
Management considers the creation of a General Services Office (GSO) who will handle the receipt, issuance and recording of the procured and issued supplies and property; and
Henceforth, Management adheres to existing laws, rules and regulations on property and supply management and safeguard government properties from loss, destruction and deterioration.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Management should strictly require all collectors to turnover their collections to the Municipal Treasurer daily and intact pursuant Section 29 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, in order to avoid the risk of loss or improper use;
The Municipal Treasurer should strictly monitor the issuance of accountable forms to the collectors by seeing to it that accountable forms issued to collectors are fully issued and collections thereof are fully remitted before a new stub is issued to them;
The Municipal Treasurer deposit her collections regularly and intact and discontinue the practice of retaining/withholding part of her collections pursuant to Section 69(4) of P. D. 1445 and Section 32 of the NGAS Manual for LGUs, Volume I, to ensure the safety and avoid risk of loss of government funds; and
Disciplinary actions or sanctions should be imposed when necessary, in order to enforce compliance with the existing rules and regulations on collection, reporting and remittances and in order to safeguard government funds.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Exert prudence in the disbursement of the LDRRMF and immediately stop the charging of monthly wages of municipal job hires against the LDRRM Fund;
Strictly utilize the LDRRM Fund for the projects/activities enumerated in Section 5 of NDRRMC, DBM and DILG Joint Circular No. 2013-1 dated March 25, 2013 dated and NDRRMC, DILG, DBM and CSC Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2014-1 dated April 4, 2014, to avoid issuance Notice of Suspensions or Disallowances;
Revert to the LDRRM Fund the amount of P1.835 million representing disbursements for payment of wages of municipal job hires in CY 2021 that were erroneously charged against the fund which shall be re-appropriated to finance only those programs, projects and activities identified to be funded under the 5% LDRRM Fund for the ensuing year.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
The Municipal Accountant exerts extra effort to review the long outstanding/stale checks and secure the addresses of the payees for notification of the return of the stale checks in their possession for replacement;
The Municipal Treasurer cancels the unclaimed stale checks and furnish the Municipal Accountant with the original Disbursement Vouchers (DV) together with its supporting documents, for the preparation of the Journal Entry Voucher following the procedures prescribed to ensure the recording of such cancellation;
The Municipal Accountant periodically coordinates with the Municipal Treasurer regarding the existence of stale checks; and
For those stale checks whose payees could no longer be located and if per record, these have been stale for many years; consider the reversion of these payables to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Enforce immediate settlement of outstanding cash advances totaling ₱247,395.36 pursuant to COA Circular No. 97-002 and COA Circular 2012-004 dated February 10, 1997 and November 28, 2012, respectively for the timely recognition of expenses in the books of accounts;
Prioritize issuance of demand letters to all accountable officers who are still in active service;
The Municipal Accountant should stop the practice of granting additional cash advances unless the previous cash advance was fully liquidated;
Impose the withholding of salary and the institution of other sanctions as provided under paragraphs 9.2 and 9.3 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997; and
Request for write-off the cash advances which have remained in active or non-moving in the books for 10 years or more and where settlement/collectivity could no longer be ascertained pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

We recommended and the Management agreed to the following:
Management includes in its Annual Budget, the budget of the Libacao College as part of its Economic Enterprise for review by the Office of the Sangguniang Panlalawigan;
Record all transactions related to the operation of the College in the General Fund as Economic Enterprise;
Close the Other Payable Account- Libacao College Special Trust Fund (LCST)in the Trust Fund books and transfer the balance of the account to the General Fund; and
The Municipal Accountant prepares and submits the financial statements of the economic enterprise for review and verification on the operation of the College in compliance with Section 313, Article II of R.A. 7160 and Section 159 of the Government Accounting Manual for LGUs.

